IPL Complete Dataset (2008-2020)¶

Introduction¶

In this blog I will be analyzing the IPL matches 2008-2020 dataset which is obtained from Kaggle. This dataset contains information about IPL (Indian premier league). It is a franchise-based cricket tournament which is played in T20 format (20 overs for each team). We will look at different analysis such as Player Analysis, Venue Analysis, most appeared umpires, Toss analysis, Date analysis, Margin of victory and Specific Team analysis at different venues.

1) Player Analysis¶

Top 20 Players with Most Player of The Match Awards¶

The player of the match award is given to the player who has performed exceptionally well in that match. Here we can see which players have received most player of the match awards over the years between 2008-2020. These players are very popular as they perform consistently and win matches for their teams on a regular basis. The graph shows AB de Villiers and CH Gayle having the most player of the match award and the graph shows the top 20 players. There are many players after this who have won less than 10 player of the match awards, since they have same number of player of the match awards it is not shown in the graph.

In [40]:
player_of_the_match = df['player_of_match'].value_counts()
Top_20_players = player_of_the_match.head(20)


#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/332289/how-do-i-change-the-size-of-figures-drawn-with-matplotlib  (for figsize)
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))

plt.xlabel('Player_name')
plt.ylabel('Number of awards')
plt.show()

2)Venue Analysis¶

The count plot shows distribution of matches across different venues. We can clearly see from the graph that Eden Gardens has hosted most matches and OUTsurance Oval has hosted least number of matches from 2008-2020. The number of matches hosted at each venue decreases as we go from Eden Gardens to OUTsurance Oval. This shows Eden Gardens is most iconic venue compared to other venues.

In [24]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))

#https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/countplot-using-seaborn-in-python/
sns.countplot(x='venue', data=df, palette='viridis', order=df['venue'].value_counts().index)
plt.title("Distribution of Matches Across Venues")
plt.xlabel('Venues')
plt.ylabel('Number of Matches')
plt.xticks(rotation=90) 

plt.show()

3)Most appeared Umpires¶

When we plot the bar chart we can clearly see that S Ravi has appeared in most of the matches and he can also be called the most senior umpire and most experienced umpire.

4)Toss Analysis¶

Here in toss analysis, from the bar graph we can see what impact does toss has on the match outcome. The X-Axis contains the Toss result and Y-Axis contains percentage of matches won. We can see from the bar graph that winning the toss has slight edge on winning the match as teams which have won the toss have won more matches than the teams which have lost the toss. Also, if we see the stacked bar chart, we can see what different teams decision is after they win the toss. The X-Axis has the team winning the toss and Y-Axis has the number of matches. We can see from the graph that Kolkata Knight Riders and Royal Challengers Bangalore are the teams which choose to field if they win the toss rather than to take bat first. Chennai Super Kings, Deccan Chargers and Pune Warriors are the only teams that prefer to bat after winning the toss compared to other teams.

In [35]:
df['toss_winner_won'] = df['toss_winner'] == df['winner']

#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/23627782/pandas-groupby-size-and-percentages
toss_impact = df.groupby('toss_winner_won').size() / len(df) * 100

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

#plotting Seaborn Barchart
sns.barplot(x=toss_impact.index, y=toss_impact.values, palette='viridis')
plt.title("Impact of Toss on Match Result")
plt.xlabel('Toss Result')
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Matches Won')
plt.xticks([0, 1], ['Lost', 'Won'], rotation=0)

#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/67112449/bar-labels-in-matplotlib-seaborn
for index, value in enumerate(toss_impact.values):
    plt.text(index, value + 0.5, f'{value:.2f}%', ha='center', va='bottom')

plt.show()

5)Date Analysis¶

5.1)Matches played in yearly basis from 2008-2020¶

Here we can see how many matches have been played in each year from 2008-2020. For this first we need to convert the date column to date time format. Then we extract the year from the date column. Then the count of matches played every year is found by using the value_counts() and it is sorted in ascending order from 2008-2020 by using sort.index(). Once this is done, we can plot a line plot using seaborn library, the X-Axis will contain year and Y-Axis will contain Number of Matches. From the line plot we can clearly see the number of matches played each year. The most number of matches is played in 2012 and 2013 with 74 matches and the least matches is played in 2014 with only 46.

In [42]:
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])


df['year'] = df['date'].dt.year


matches_played_every_year = df['year'].value_counts().sort_index()



plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

#LinePlot
#https://seaborn.pydata.org/generated/seaborn.lineplot.html
sns.lineplot(x=matches_played_every_year.index, y=matches_played_every_year.values, marker='o', color='blue')

plt.title("Number of Matches Played Each Year", fontsize=18)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel('Number of Matches', fontsize=16)

plt.show()

5.2) Distribution of Matches Across Months¶

Here like yearly analysis, the months are extracted from the date column and count of matches played every month is found and it is reordered by using reindex () since the month names were not in order. We are plotting a seaborn bar chart using seaborn library, the X-Axis will contain Month and Y-Axis will contain Number of matches. From the bar chart we can clearly see that the number of matches played is very high for April and May and we can hardly see a few matches which is played in the month of June, September, and November.

In [43]:
df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['date'])
df['month'] = df['date'].dt.month_name()
matches_per_month = df['month'].value_counts().sort_index()
matches_per_month = df['month'].value_counts().reindex(['March', 'April', 'May', 'June', 'September','November'])

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

#plotting Barchart
sns.barplot(x=matches_per_month.index, y=matches_per_month.values, palette='viridis')
plt.title("Distribution of Matches Across Months")
plt.xlabel('Month')
plt.ylabel('Number of Matches')
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')  

plt.show()

5.3) Distribution of Matches Across Days of the Week¶

Here like Distribution of Matches Across months. The days of the week are sorted in order from Monday to Sunday. A bar chart is plotted using seaborn library. The X-Axis will contain Day of the week and Y-Axis will contain Number of Matches. It is no surprise that the number of matches played peaks during the weekend (Saturday and Sunday) and Monday has relatively a less number of matches played compared to other days of the week.

7) Specific Team Analysis at Top 10 Venues Where they have Played Most of their matches¶

Here I have taken the team which I like the most (Royal Challengers Bangalore). We are replacing M Chinnaswamy Stadium with its own name as it has repeated 2 times since we are taking 2 columns of data one for team 1 and another for team 2. We are then calculating their performance at the top 10 venues where they have played most of their matches. We then calculate the number of wins and losses at each venue along with the total number of matches played. From the Stacked bar graph, we can see that the whole bar represents the total number of matches played at each venue and green color bar represents the total number of wins at that venue and red color bar represents the total number of losses at those venues. They have played most of their matches at M Chinnaswamy Stadium as this is their home ground. In terms of performance, they have performed very well at Feroz shah Kotla where they have more wins than losses. Their performance at Rajiv Gandhi International Stadium, Uppal and MA Chidambaram stadium, Chepauk where they have more losses than wins.

In [49]:
My_favourite_team = 'Royal Challengers Bangalore'
RCB_matches = df[(df['team1'] == My_favourite_team) | (df['team2'] == My_favourite_team)].copy()
RCB_matches['venue'] = RCB_matches['venue'].replace({'M Chinnaswamy Stadium': 'M.Chinnaswamy Stadium'})
venue_Total_matches = RCB_matches['venue'].value_counts()
top_10_venues = venue_Total_matches.head(10)

# Counting wins and losses at each venue
RCB_wins = df[df['winner'] == My_favourite_team]
RCB_wins['venue'] = RCB_wins['venue'].replace({'M Chinnaswamy Stadium': 'M.Chinnaswamy Stadium'})
venue_wins = RCB_wins['venue'].value_counts()

RCB_losses = RCB_matches[RCB_matches['winner'] != My_favourite_team]
venue_losses = RCB_losses['venue'].value_counts()


plt.figure(figsize=(14, 7))

#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/65986403/using-range-and-length-function-together-in-python
index = range(len(top_10_venues))

#https://www.tutorialkart.com/matplotlib-tutorial/matplotlib-pyplot-stacked-bar-plot/#gsc.tab=0
plt.bar(index, venue_Total_matches.loc[top_10_venues.index], bar_width, label='Total Matches', color='black', alpha=0.5)
plt.bar(index, venue_wins.loc[top_10_venues.index], bar_width, label='Wins', color='green')
plt.bar(index, venue_losses.loc[top_10_venues.index], bar_width, label='Losses', color='red', bottom=venue_wins.loc[top_10_venues.index])

#plotting Stacked Bar Chart
plt.xlabel('Venue')
plt.ylabel('Number of Matches')
plt.title('Matches Played, Won, and Lost by Royal Challengers Bangalore at Top 10 Venues')

Conclusion:¶

To conclude, we have found that the players with the most player of match are AB de Villiers and CH Gayle. The most used Venue is Eden Gardens. Toss decision by teams - Kolkata Knight Riders prefer to field most of the times if they win the toss and Chennai Super Kings prefer to bat most of the times if they win the toss. The most number of matches were played in the year 2012 and 2013 and there was a sudden drop in the number of matches played in the year 2014. Most of the matches are played in the months of April and May. Distribution of matches peaked on Saturday and Sunday. Match won by wickets is more than more than match won by runs. Royal Challengers Bangalore have played most of their matches at M Chinnaswamy Stadium as this is their home ground. In terms of performance, they have performed very well at Feroz shah Kotla where they have more wins than losses. Their performance at Rajiv Gandhi International Stadium, Uppal, and MA Chidambaram stadium, Chepauk where they have more losses than wins.
